                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d262">
                <head>262. Letter From President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="from"
                        >Kennedy</persName> to the President of the Cuban Revolutionary Council
                        (<persName corresp="#p_MCJ3" type="to">Miro Cardona</persName>)<note n="0"
                        type="source" xml:id="d262fn0">Source: Department of State, <gloss
                            target="#t_INR1">INR</gloss>/IL Historical Files, Cuba, August 1961-.
                        Secret. A note on the source text indicates that the letter was seen and
                        approved by <persName corresp="#p_HRA3">Hurwitch</persName>, Vallon,
                            <persName corresp="#p_CWDR1">Coerr</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_WRE1">Woodward</persName>, <persName>Braddock</persName>,
                        and <persName>Wollam</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-09-14">September 14, 1961</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Dr. <persName corresp="#p_MCJ3">Miro
                            Cardona</persName>
                    </hi>: I write to express my confidence in your leadership of the Cuban
                    Revolutionary Council. The United States Government deeply admires the
                    distinguished service you have already rendered to the cause of a free Cuba; and
                    I hope you will continue to lead this fight until your country is liberated from
                    the tyranny which has been imposed on it. I am sure that any problems arising
                    from your relationship with the United States can be worked out in the spirit of
                    mutual cooperation and common aspirations which lie behind all our efforts.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">
                            <hi rend="strong">John F. Kennedy</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="1" xml:id="d262fn1">Printed from a copy that indicates President
                                <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> signed the
                            original.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
